            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--this is the large block with frag. of 4 or 5 aedicola reliefs, of which A (top left) carries the text. The largest block, 5 aedicola partially represented, A carries the following text: charisteria Paidessi kai Annai kai Apolloni, epi amphipolou en Surakousais - mi- - - hiereias de tan Paidon Kaikilias, hoi paragenomenoi pot Numphas kai eucharistesantes menos Apellaiou tritai: L. Makris Longos, K. Oppis Kanakis, K. Ampious Kreskes, A. Ailis Sellaris, K. -esis -tianos, G. -iph-kratos, G. - -metos. This and the others from a cave at Buscemi, nr. Acrae; cf. the others published best also in PdP 6 (1951), and also IG XIV.204 (Acrae) for related 'hagnai theai'; P-C discusses other relevant material also. In general, note the Roman names in most of these; also the persistence of the amphipolis at Syracuse (cf. DS XVI.70.6), and the  amphipolis of the Paides, probably the eponymous amphipolis for Acrae (presumably the local city concerned). P-C observes that the 'koreion' attested in IG XIV.217 could perhaps be associated with this cult also, although P-C thinks that the Demeter-Korai and Paides cults should be kept separate in this case, although considerable overlap generally likely / common. The material in the cave doesn't go back past the C3 BC, and the whole institution is presumaly Timoleontic or later.  cf. ASNP 1981, p.1069ff for 2 oracle inscrs. from Akrai region with mentions of Nymphs and Paides. On the amphipolis, Diodorus XVI.70.6 writes that it was the eponymous office at Syracuse  'down to the time of my writing this history and of the change in their form of government. For when the Romans shared their citizenship with the Sikeliotes, the office of the amphipoloi became insignficant, after having been important for over three hundred years.'--></p>
